You are given the following Python implementation of the PageRank algorithm for a directed graph. The graph is represented as a dictionary where keys are node identifiers and values are lists of destination nodes for each outgoing edge. Identify all bugs in the code. For each bug, explain why it is problematic and under what conditions it manifests. Then provide a fully corrected implementation that: handles dangling nodes (nodes with no out-edges) correctly by distributing their rank uniformly, includes all nodes that appear as link targets even if they have no outgoing edges themselves, does not mutate the input graph, avoids false convergence, and has reasonable time complexity (i.e., does not use O(N^2) nested loops over all node pairs when checking incoming edges). 

```python
def page_rank(graph, d=0.85, max_iter=100, tol=1e-6):
    N = len(graph)
    if N == 0:
        return {}

    nodes = list(graph.keys())
    rank = {node: 1.0 / N for node in nodes}
    new_rank = {}

    for i in range(max_iter):
        for node in nodes:
            rank_sum = 0.0
            for n in nodes:
                if node in graph[n]:
                    out_degree = len(graph[n])
                    if out_degree == 0:
                        out_degree = N
                    rank_sum += rank[n] / out_degree
            new_rank[node] = (1.0 - d) / N + d * rank_sum

        diff = sum(abs(new_rank[node] - rank[node]) for node in nodes)
        rank = new_rank
        if diff < tol:
            break

    return rank
```

